<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>SINGLE SPEED REAR AXLE: INTERNATIONAL - ASSEMBLE</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcsubsec>
        <title>ASSEMBLE</title>
        <svcproc svcproctype="assemble" graphiccount="15">
            <title>PINION (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1400830">Figure 30</hotlnk>)
            </title>
            <figure id="f1400830" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1400830" filename="../figg14/G1400830.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 30. Pinion Assembly - Exploded View</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Press inner pinion bearing cone onto the pinion gear (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1400831">Figure 31</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1400831" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1400831" filename="../figg14/G1400831.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 31. Inner Pinion Bearing Cone</caption>
                </figure>
                <para></para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Press roller bearing onto pinion gear (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1400832">Figure 32</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1400832" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1400832" filename="../figg14/G1400832.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 32. Roller Bearing</caption>
                </figure>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Bearing must be installed with radius in bore toward pinion gear.</para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Stake roller bearing in nine places, using a staking tool (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1400833">Figure 33</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1400833" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1400833" filename="../figg14/G1400833.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 33. Stake Roller Bearing</caption>
                </figure>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Make sure all cage bores are free of nicks, dirt, or any contamination.</para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install inner pinion bearing cup into pinion cage (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1400834">Figure 34</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1400834" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1400834" filename="../figg14/G1400834.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 34. Inner Pinion Bearing Cup</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install outer pinion bearing cup into pinion cage (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1400835">Figure 35</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1400835" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1400835" filename="../figg14/G1400835.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 35. Outer Pinion Bearing Cup</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Use a feeler gauge or shim stock (.0015 approx.) to ensure bearing cups are completely
                    seated in bearing bores. This is necessary for proper pinion position (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1400836">Figure 36</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1400836" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1400836" filename="../figg14/G1400836.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 36. Check With Feeler Gauge</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Place selective preload spacer removed during disassembly onto pinion (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1400837">Figure 37</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1400837" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1400837" filename="../figg14/G1400837.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 37. Selective Preload Spacer</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Place pinion cage onto pinion gear inner bearing (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1400838">Figure 38</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1400838" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1400838" filename="../figg14/G1400838.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 38. Pinion Cage</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install outer pinion bearing cone onto pinion (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1400839">Figure 39</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1400839" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1400839" filename="../figg14/G1400839.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 39. Outer Pinion Bearing Cone</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Inspect end yoke seal surface for grooves caused by lip of seal. If grooves can be
                    detected with a fingernail, it should be replaced.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install end yoke onto pinion without seal to allow proper setting of bearing preload.
                    Tighten pinion nut to 900 to 1200 ft-lbs. (1220 to 1627 N&#8226;m) (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1400840">Figure 40</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1400840" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1400840" filename="../figg14/G1400840.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 40. Install End Yoke</caption>
                </figure>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Pinion cage should be rotated while tightening pinion nut to seat and align the pinion
                            bearings.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">There are two methods of measuring pinion bearing preload and both are acceptable.
                    Mechanic's preference and available tools determine which method will be used. Both methods measure
                    torque to rotate.
                </para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">To measure preload with the spring scale, clamp the end yoke horizontally in a
                        soft-jawed vise. Attach one end of cord to a bolt hole in the pinion cage, wrap cord around
                        pinion cage and attach the other end of cord to the spring scale. Rotate pinion cage by pulling
                        scale. Read scale during fourth revolution. Scale reading must be between 3 and 9 lbs. (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1400841">Figure 41</hotlnk>).
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f1400841" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g1400841" filename="../figg14/G1400841.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 41. Measure Preload - Spring Scale</caption>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">To measure preload with the inch pound torque wrench, assemble pinion cage into the
                        carrier housing and install two mounting bolts to anchor the unit. Rotate pinion gear with inch
                        pound torque wrench as shown. Torque measurement will be taken during fourth revolution and must
                        be between 10 and 30 in-lbs. (1.1 and 3.4 N&#8226;m) without pinion seal (rear) (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1400842">Figure 42</hotlnk>).
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f1400842" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g1400842" filename="../figg14/G1400842.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 42. Measure Preload - Torque Wrench</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <specpara>
                        <note>
                            <para>When preload reading does not fall within allowable limits, bearing load can be
                                increased by using a thinner spacer or decreased by using a thicker spacer.
                            </para>
                        </note>
                    </specpara>
                    <specpara>
                        <note>
                            <para>.001 inch (.025 mm) change in preload spacer thickness changes scale reading by
                                approximately 10 lbs. .001 change in preload spacer will change torque to rotate by
                                approximately 30 in-lbs. (This is only a guide. Individual carriers may vary slightly.)
                            </para>
                        </note>
                    </specpara>
                    <para>Refer to
                        <hotlnk xrefid="hl1400803">Available Spacer Thickness Table</hotlnk>, for available spacer
                        thicknesses. Measure the spacer before assembly to assure correct thickness.
                    </para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
